Data Analysis of Week 3 Example Data

Monique Estrada

2023-07-26

Overview

This report presents primary data analysis for the Week 3 example data. Specifically, this will report basic descriptive statistics as well as report tests of the following predictions:

  1. People will feel more guilt when:
  • 1.1. They caused the shock (vs. their partner)
  • 1.2. The partner is morally good (vs. bad)
  • 1.3. The shock is stronger (high > medium > low)
  1. Women will report more guilt than men
  2. agreeable people will report more guilt
  3. Neurotic people will report more guilt

and

  1. People will be more generous when:
  • 5.1 They caused the shock (vs. their partner)
  • 5.2 The partner is morally good (vs. bad)
  • 5.3 The shock is stronger (high > medium > low)
  1. Women will be more generous than men
  2. agreeable people will be more generous
  3. Neurotic people will be more generous
#Load in the data
data<-read.csv("Week 3/Processed Data/Week 3 Data PROCESSED.csv")

#Recode variables:
data$PIN<-as.factor(data$PIN)
data$sex<-as.factor(data$sex)
data$shock<-factor(data$shock,levels=c("low","medium","high"))
data$shockCause<-as.factor(data$shockCause)
data$pMoral<-as.factor(data$pMoral)

Guilt Analyses

Prediction 1.1

Prediction 1.1 was supported. People felt more guilty when they caused the shock:

#Run the t-test for prediction 1.1
p1.1<-t.test(data$guilt~data$shockCause)

#Output the result
p1.1
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  data$guilt by data$shockCause
## t = -11.016, df = 708.25, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group partner and group self is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.1502070 -0.8022365
## sample estimates:
## mean in group partner    mean in group self 
##              3.511173              4.487395
#Generate the graph
plot1.1 <-ggplot(data=data,
                 aes(x = shockCause,
                     y=guilt,
                     fill=shockCause)) +
  labs(x="Cause of Shock", 
       y="Guilt") + 
  stat_summary(fun = "mean", 
               geom ="bar",
               position = "dodge") + 
  stat_summary(fun.data="mean_cl_boot",
               geom="errorbar",
               position="dodge")+
  scale_x_discrete(labels=c("Partner","Self"))+
    scale_fill_manual(values=c("yellow", "purple"),
                               guide=F)+
    theme_grey(base_size=20)

#Output the graph 
plot1.1

Prediction 1.3

Prediction 1.3 was supported. People felt more guilty when the shock was stronger:

Generosity Analyses

#Melt the data for within-subjects analyses
dataMelt<-melt(data,
               measure.vars=c("preShare","postShare"),
               variable.name=c("prePost"),
               value.name=c("share"))
